## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why This Breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — there is no way to forcibly terminate a managed thread. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Pattern Classification

| Original Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Cleanup on cancellation | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Just continue the loop (OCE doesn't auto-rethrow) |
| `GetNextItem()` blocking | Blocking call interruption | Pass `CancellationToken` to unblock |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — equivalent to old ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — OperationCanceledException doesn't auto-rethrow.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to exit gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit — it's stuck in uncooperative code.
            // Log a warning; you cannot force-kill it in modern .NET.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes to `GetNextItem`

The blocking `GetNextItem()` **must** accept and honor the token — otherwise cancellation stalls:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private object GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// AFTER: throws OperationCanceledException when token is cancelled
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
// Works with BlockingCollection<T>, Channel<T>, SemaphoreSlim, etc.
```

If `GetNextItem` uses raw `Monitor.Wait` or `AutoResetEvent.WaitOne`, replace with:

```csharp
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| Not passing `CancellationToken` to `GetNextItem` | `Stop()` will hang — the thread stays blocked forever since nothing can interrupt it |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and registered callbacks |
| Expecting cancellation to be instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint — if `ProcessItem` takes 30s, cancellation waits |
| Using `Thread.Sleep` in any remaining code | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation can interrupt the wait |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated exceptions |

### If `ProcessItem` Is Long-Running

Add checkpoints inside it:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(object item, CancellationToken token)
{
    Step1(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
    Step2(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
    Step3(item);
}
```

### The Fundamental Shift

**.NET Framework:** The runtime *injects* `ThreadAbortException` into your thread at arbitrary points — your code is a passive victim.

**.NET 8:** Your code must *voluntarily check* `CancellationToken` and throw — if it doesn't check, it can't be stopped. Design checkpoint frequency based on your acceptable stop-latency.
